This day will always stay reminiscent for me when I look back to it in the coming future.
Today, I nearly skipped the practice. At night, when I was on the verge of dozing off to my dreamland - my heart recalled my mat. I felt a little guilt rushing inside me for being forgetful about my commitment towards myself.
I was in a dilemma whether to sleep off, or show up. 
I recollected Adriene mam's words from one of the practices - showing up to the mat is a great way to say, I Love You. 
Her words echoed inside my mind, " You are committed, you have to show up, no.matter.what."
And so I did.
Without caring of the timing or the sleepy environment, I showed up, at 11PM.
After the practice, when here I am uplifted from the heart - I caressed the mat and softly gazed at it, pondering over how dedicated I am, of how strong the bond of love I have with myself is. As you said Adriene, I showed up - no.matter.what. And I am intrigued over the how much I love myself.
I am proud of myself.
I am proud to have showed up.
Now is when I have finally realized - the hardest part, indeed, is showing up.
This incident is a reminder to myself and to everyone reading - that you are dedicated - and you will show up.
Stay committed to yourself, because you certainly deserve the love.
Namaste.

I experienced my own resilience during this practice. When I came to the mat I became aware of all my emotions from today. Turns out that once I slowed down and took the time, I found I am tired, scared, and craving some time to do things that I want to do, not things I have to do. And so as I struggled through this practice I noticed myself channeling the strength inside me to just keep going. I took the extra breaths and extra time to make sure that I just kept going. 
In my life I used to quit, and look for cheap comforts wherever I broke down. Now I keep chugging, because i have a good life somewhere down the road, and if I stop I won't get there. "these woods are lovely dark and deep, but I have promises to keep. And miles to go before I sleep"

Thanks, Adriene (and Benji)! Some thoughts from me today:

1. I was ready for today's session. I've had a long day of not moving very much (less than usual, even). Today was probably the first day when I was eagerly anticipating the yoga for itself rather than just for the satisfaction of getting another day in the sequence, if that makes sense. I'm pleased to say it met my expectations and I found it thoroughly uplifting!
2. Ten days ago, I'd never ever done a "downward facing dog", but today it feels like returning home. As soon as you name it, I know where I am. It's a known, familiar place to be.
3. I creak like an old wardrobe in some of those poses. Which probably tells you how inflexible I am and how little I move around during the rest of my day!
4. By the end of that, when I was on my back, my arms and hands were perfectly relaxed. I could have moved them, but they were just so relaxed that I didn't want to disturb them. So I have to admit I didn't join you in that final seat until a little late.

Just hearing the first few notes of the intro music, I feel like I'm putting down a heavy load. I already feel stronger than I did day 1. I even tried (and somewhat succeeded) at holding my leg with alternate arm. I wasn't going to try, but Adriene encouraged me and it was an uplifting moment, both literally and metaphorically! So appreciative of the whole YWA team for this positive way to start 2022. ðŸ™

Y'all I don't want to shift the focus from the great video and practice but I want to share something with you, as I see in the comments a lot of folks are dealing with a hard time. Sometimes I like to think like that what seems like this bad luck that is following us is just one small step away from getting things finally work. Some small, even random step, like the butterfly effect kind of way. Like a hidden small quest from the destiny that even makes no sense. Like, I'll finally land my dream job once I set foot at the coffee shop in my building (like, I've been living here for ages but never ever visited). Or I'll finally find true love once I finally wear that dress I bought years ago but always told my self, I'll wear it some other time. The thing is, stuff might be hard sometimes but you might need just a little push, so things start getting good again! and guess what, since you are here on this yoga journey, you are already on the right path. Just remember, have courage, have faith, work hard and be a good and loving person. And if you believe at least a little bit in magic, guess what - reading this weird comment of mine is the little sign you've needed to know things will be alright! You're here at the right place and time :) And keep doing yoga, kudos to Adriene who's awesome.

Subtle Adriene! Sneaking in a backbend class without fanfare. I have practised yoga for some years, and used to attend yoga classes regularly, twice a week until a few years ago I found I couldn't, didn't want to, face the London commute to get to and from classes. Practising Iyengar Yoga, the 'back bend' class was always the third week of the month (preceded by standing poses first week, sitting low ground poses second week, resting fourth and final week). If back bends wasn't really your thing, (and it wasn't/isn't mine), there was plenty time to anticipate with some apprehension for me, the tough, challenging and demanding back bend class. Not so with today's, Day 10, Uplift practice! At some point during the practice it dawned on me, 'hey, this is a back bend session!'. Congratulations Adriene for easing us into this, mindfully, gently and yes, it was uplifting, and yes, it was also centering. I salute you Adriene! ðŸ™
